hands_on_practices.introduction:
Tensors possess internal structures and symmetries that often correspond to deep physical principles. In this practice, we will explore the concepts of symmetry and antisymmetry by constructing rank-2 tensors from vectors [@problem_id:1853220]. Understanding how to identify or create symmetric ($T^{\mu
u} = T^{
u\mu}$) and antisymmetric ($T^{\mu
u} = -T^{
u\mu}$) tensors is a crucial skill, as this decomposition has profound physical significance, for instance, in describing the electromagnetic field.

hands_on_practices.solution:
We are given two 4-vectors with components $A^{\mu}$ and $B^{
u}$, and two rank-2 contravariant tensors defined by $C^{\mu
u} = A^{\mu}B^{
u} + B^{\mu}A^{
u}$ and $D^{\mu
u} = A^{\mu}B^{
u} - B^{\mu}A^{
u}$. A tensor $T^{\mu
u}$ is symmetric if $T^{\mu
u} = T^{
u\mu}$ and antisymmetric if $T^{\mu
u} = -T^{
u\mu}$ for all $\mu,
u$.

To test the symmetry of $C^{\mu
u}$, compute its transpose in indices:
$$
C^{
u\mu} = A^{
u}B^{\mu} + B^{
u}A^{\mu}.
$$
Using commutativity of real-number multiplication of components, $A^{
u}B^{\mu} = B^{\mu}A^{
u}$ and $B^{
u}A^{\mu} = A^{\mu}B^{
u}$. Therefore,
$$
C^{
u\mu} = B^{\mu}A^{
u} + A^{\mu}B^{
u} = A^{\mu}B^{
u} + B^{\mu}A^{
u} = C^{\mu
u},
$$
which holds for all $\mu,
u$. Hence $C^{\mu
u}$ is symmetric.

To test the antisymmetry of $D^{\mu
u}$, compute:
$$
D^{
u\mu} = A^{
u}B^{\mu} - B^{
u}A^{\mu}.
$$
Again using commutativity, rewrite $A^{
u}B^{\mu} = B^{\mu}A^{
u}$ and $B^{
u}A^{\mu} = A^{\mu}B^{
u}$ to get
$$
D^{
u\mu} = B^{\mu}A^{
u} - A^{\mu}B^{
u} = -(A^{\mu}B^{
u} - B^{\mu}A^{
u}) = -D^{\mu
u}.
$$
Thus $D^{\mu
u}$ is antisymmetric.

Therefore, $C^{\mu
u}$ is symmetric and $D^{\mu
u}$ is antisymmetric, independent of the specific numerical components of $A^{\mu}$ and $B^{
u}$.
